Rel.: 1999
</p>

<p>Excerpts:<br>
[1]-[4] <a href="hmu8167.htm">Harmonia Mundi &quot;Century&quot;
HMX 290 8167</a> [CD] A History of Music, vol. 5: La naissance de
la Polyphonie / The Birth of Polyphony
</p>

<p>This is a rather thorough examination of the medieval technique
of hocket, although curiously, the most famous example
(<a href="../composers/machaut/h1.html">that by Machaut</a>) is
not included.  The hocket is an early form of voice interchange,
perhaps anticipating such more modern techniques as imitation or
fugue, and occurs with rests in one voice directly opposite melody
in the other among the pair usually taking part.  The present
program explores various examples from the 13th &amp; 14th century,
together with some non-hocket works included for contrast.  One
significant point is that often the two voices of a hocket are not
equal, as one will be active much more than the other.</p>

